DR Congo: Humanitarian Information Note -- Ebola virus disease epidemic in Equateur, 18 Sep 2020, report 84
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Key figures and facts
- Preparation activities in risk areas need to be strengthened.
- Payment to service providers has started in Bikoro.

Overview of the situation
--------------------
The epidemiological situation of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in Ecuador is marked by high mobility of contacts in the province. WHO has strengthened the follow-up of contacts with support activities which encourage them to stay in their communities.

Good preparation in high-risk health zones is also necessary.

The Preparation Commission carried out integrated training (surveillance, communication, prevention, and control of infections) in the health zones of Basankusu, Loukolela, and Irebu. It is imperative to strengthen these activities in order to allow areas not yet affected to prepare to respond in time, and to bring the epidemic under rapid control.

It is essential that the multisectoral preparation in risk areas be assumed by the Ministry of Public Health (MSP). It will strengthen the institutional and community anchoring of this activity.

The active search for the 6 contacts lost to follow-up in the Bomongo health zone is intensifying in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and neighboring Republic of Congo. To pool research efforts, response teams are pursuing consultations through the Ministries of Health of the 2 countries and the WHO.

Food support for sick and cured people remains a necessity. The support of partners is essential. A WFP [UN World Food Programme] delegation met with the coordination of the response and some partners (PRONANUT [National Nutrition Program], UNICEF, WHO, and OCHA) in order to specify the practical modalities to assist these people.

The payments to service providers began on Fri 18 Sep in the Bikoro health zone. Several providers in the health zone had suspended their participation in response activities, requiring the payment of their premiums in advance. This situation affected the activities of the response in Bikoro. The rise of alerts has decreased while this area is experiencing a significant number of community deaths. The payroll team plans to continue this operation in other health zones.

The province of Equateur recorded 7 new confirmed cases of COVID-19, after mass collections organized on 1 Sep 2020. These cases are asymptomatic, and now remain in self-isolation. To date, the province of Equateur has recorded 14 confirmed cases including 3 deaths from COVID-19, distributed in 3 health zones.

- Wed 16 Sep 2020
[OCHA (UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs) in French, machine trans., edited]
https://reliefweb.int/report/democratic-republic-congo/rd-congo-note-d-information-humanitaire-epid-mie-de-la-maladie-76

DR Congo: Humanitarian Information Note -- Ebola virus disease epidemic in Equateur -- 15 Sep 2020, report 81
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Key figures and facts
- A new affected health area in the Bikoro health zone.
- Visit of the Swedish cooperation and ECHO in the province of Equateur.

Overview of the situation
-------------------------
Cases of infection of children aged 0-5 are back in the province of Equateur. 2 children whose Ebola virus disease (EVD) was confirmed on 14 Sep 2020 are 2 months and 5 years old. They were reported in the health areas of Ngelo Monzoi and Botende, in the Bikoro health zone. The Ngelo Monzoi health area has just notified its 1st case, bringing the number of health areas affected by Ebola in Equateur province to 40. These cases, like most, have been exposed to the disease within the community.

A delegation from Swedish cooperation and the European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations (ECHO), arrived on Tue 15 Sep 2020 in Mbandaka to follow up on projects funded through FAO, Oxfam, and Action Against Hunger (ACF) in Equateur province. The delegation met the response partners the same day to discuss the epidemiological situation as well as the multisectoral response in support of the health response against Ebola. These discussions also focused on the opportunity to strengthen the province's health system, and to set up programs aimed at increasing the resilience capacity of the populations. On Wed 16 Sep 2020, this delegation will visit the projects implemented by Oxfam and ACF in the Bikoro health zone.

