Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Patients presenting with hemorrhagic fevers caused by Lassa and Ebola viruses have symptoms that include fever, headache, muscle pain, weakness, fatigue, and vomiting that cannot distinguish causation, even though symptoms tend to be more severe in Ebola cases. In severe cases, both diseases can cause bleeding from the gums, eyes, and nose, which can lead to organ failure and death.

Lassa, as opposed to Ebola, can also cause tremors, facial swelling, respiratory distress, and encephalitis in serious cases. Lassa also can cause varying degrees of deafness in mild and severe cases -- oftentimes, the hearing loss is permanent. This happens in about 1/3 of infections, according to the CDC.

Having a point of care test that can identify the 2 viruses and distinguish between them would be a big advance allowing Ebola patients to be separated from patients with other etiologies, preventing its spread. In addition the test is affordable at a cost of USD 1 and proper treatment can be started much faster without having to wait days for a diagnosis. - Mod.LK

Maps of Congo DR: http://goo.gl/DM2AT8 and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7803256,194]
